On October 27 and 28, 2020, the Future of Privacy Forum (FPF) Education and Innovation Foundation convened an international group of 350 computer science, privacy law, social science, and health information experts representing 32 countries in a Convergence Accelerator (C-Accel) workshop titled, "Privacy and Pandemics: Responsible Use of Data During Times of Crisis," to examine benefits, risks and strategies for the collection and protection of data in support of public health initiatives specific to COVID-19 and beyond. 

Workshop preparation included a call for proposals that led to selection of 51 position papers organized in four sessions across tech-policy-legal-ethical dimensions: (1) Accessibility of Data to Track SARS CoV-2 Infections; (2) Use of Technology to Track, Trace &amp; Notify to Control Spread of COVID-19; (3) Adapting Legal and Regulatory Responses to a Global Emergency; and (4) Convergence of Technology, Policy and Responsible Data Use in a Global Crisis. In addition to FPF and NSF, co-sponsoring organizations in the workshop included Duke Sanford School of Public Policy, SFI ADAPT Research Centre, Dublin City University, Intel Corporation, OneTrust, and the Israel Tech Policy Institute (an FPF affiliate). 

Based upon the insights from the workshop, FPF produced a publicly available final report, "NSF Convergence Accelerator Privacy and Pandemics: Responsible Use of Data During Times of Crisis," published on December 22, 2020. The report lays out a case for conducting research that addresses responsible uses of technology and data during crisis situations as a first-order priority of the NSF and adjacent US federal funding bodies. Based on FPF's analysis of leading research and expert positions, the report recommends that NSF consider the following roadmap to point the way forward in research directions, practice improvements, and development of privacy-preserving products and services to inform responses to the COVID-19 crisis and in preparation for future pandemics and other crises: 

- Support the refinement and application of existing privacy-preserving and privacy-enhancing technologies that can support public health goals while mitigating privacy risks. Promising approaches include: decentralized contact tracing, homomorphic encryption, and differential privacy; 

- Support the development of emerging privacy-enhancing technologies that hold promise in the public health sphere. Emerging technologies include: synthetic data, controlled access environments, digital twins, and simulations; 

- Support cross-disciplinary research into privacy-protective approaches to key emerging technologies, including Wireless Sensor Networks and data processing strategies for on-device and/or centralized analysis of personal health information; 

- Explore mechanisms to balance the need for increased access to data that allows researchers to understand the differential impacts of crises on certain communities by not obscuring critical community characteristics with privacy-enhancing technologies; 

- Convene cross-disciplinary experts to create and refine guidance for implementation of privacy protections suited to crisis situations; 

- Identify top-priority updates to laws and regulations pertaining to public health; 

- Explore mechanisms that promote data interoperability while promoting privacy; 

- Promote the development of promising de-identification technologies and mitigation strategies to address re-identification risks; 

- Promote practical, implementable ethical frameworks that go beyond the FAIR principles; 

- Identify practical lessons learned during the COVID-19 pandemic regarding publication ethics and norms for research in a time of crisis that can apply to future crises.

In production of the workshop and final report, the project shared knowledge to address the needs of the public health community and government leaders in the COVID-19 emergency and encouraged these leaders to communicate with each other, with tech companies, and with researchers to innovate and collaborate to meet those needs. From researcher-led discussions, the project created a base of new knowledge and action strategies for sharing data responsibly in the COVID crisis and identified research priorities to improve data governance systems and structures for future pandemics. Through its multi-stakeholder engagement and interdisciplinary approach, the project emphasized (and established) how private-public partnerships and tech-regulatory solutions will be necessary in combination to ensure and advance responsible use of data during current and future crises. In the broadest sense, this Convergence Accelerator project contributes to improved data governance systems with individual privacy at the forefront and reinforces the need for investment as a national priority to achieve this outcome.

